        },
        {
            "paragraph": "**"
        },
        {
            "paragraph": "Not all of these projects follow the exact set of methods described, but they all represent a level of attention and intentionality that navigating the internet doesn’t usually afford."
        },
        {
            "paragraph": "If the most common metaphor for algorithms is following a recipe, then the goal shouldn’t be to stop making food, but to become so attuned to the shape of cooking that we can make substitutions and eventually, our own recipes. If we’re bold enough to question the maps we've been given, we may discover a world richer, stranger, and more alive than anything an algorithm could drop at our feet."
        },
        {
            "paragraph": "Elan Ullendorff is a designer, writer, and educator based in Philadelphia. He currently serves as Director of Product at The Marshall Project and teaches at both Penn Engineering and the School for Poetic Computation. He writes a newsletter called Escape the Algorithm about reclaiming attention and finding a more human side of the internet."
        }
